00:22:16,836 --> 00:22:19,812
I realized I had no recollection
of the previous night.

512
00:22:19,844 --> 00:22:23,908
I came in here.
Found my sweet Monica.

513
00:22:25,796 --> 00:22:29,859
I ran back to the kitchen,
dialed 911.

514
00:22:29,892 --> 00:22:33,412
There was a shattered vase.

515
00:22:33,444 --> 00:22:35,300
Anyhow,
when the ambulance arrived,

516
00:22:35,332 --> 00:22:36,996
they told me
she was already gone

517
00:22:37,028 --> 00:22:39,715
and had been
for quite some time.

518
00:22:42,212 --> 00:22:44,964
Does anyone else have keys?

519
00:22:44,996 --> 00:22:47,812
Only Rosario. That's our nanny.

520
00:22:47,844 --> 00:22:50,500
And she was in Venezuela
visiting her family.

521
00:22:50,532 --> 00:22:51,876
Nanny?

522
00:22:51,908 --> 00:22:53,540
You have kids in the house?

523
00:22:53,572 --> 00:22:56,452
Yes.
We have one child, Gaby.

524
00:22:56,484 --> 00:22:58,180
She likely wasn't
the killer either,

525
00:22:58,212 --> 00:23:00,260
but she'll be home
from kindergarten soon enough

526
00:23:00,292 --> 00:23:03,140
if you think it's worth
trying to wrest a confession.

527
00:23:03,172 --> 00:23:05,316
Pretty glib, considering.

528
00:23:05,348 --> 00:23:06,852
ALASTAIR:
Forgive me.

529
00:23:06,884 --> 00:23:09,700
Dear Gaby doesn't even know,
of course, but...

530
00:23:11,684 --> 00:23:14,404
...the world is certain
I murdered my wife, Mr. Waldo,

531
00:23:14,436 --> 00:23:17,796
and I can't even tell you
the world is wrong.

532
00:23:17,828 --> 00:23:20,420
If you know a man who's handled
a similar predicament

533
00:23:20,452 --> 00:23:22,948
with more élan, point me to him,

534
00:23:22,980 --> 00:23:25,860
and I shall gladly emulate.

535
00:23:25,891 --> 00:23:28,132
You ever thought about trying
to stop drinking?

536
00:23:31,268 --> 00:23:34,179
All the time.

537
00:23:34,212 --> 00:23:37,956
But this doesn't seem the week
for that, now, does it?

538
00:23:37,988 --> 00:23:39,331
Daddy!

539
00:23:39,364 --> 00:23:41,540
Princess Ozma,
where did you come from?

540
00:23:41,572 --> 00:23:43,300
Oh, oh, oh.

541
00:23:43,332 --> 00:23:46,436
Want to hear the song Little Dog
taught us at school today?

542
00:23:46,468 --> 00:23:48,868
ALASTAIR: A little dog?
Why, yes, of course.

543
00:23:48,900 --> 00:23:52,100
♪ Brush every morning,
brush every night ♪

544
00:23:52,132 --> 00:23:56,196
♪ I brush and I brush
so my teeth will be white ♪

545
00:23:56,228 --> 00:23:59,524
♪ Teeth can be shiny,
teeth can be gold ♪

546
00:23:59,556 --> 00:24:03,492
♪ I hope I still have some
when I'm very old ♪

547
00:24:03,524 --> 00:24:04,803
[ Laughs ]

548
00:24:04,836 --> 00:24:06,564
- You know it.
- I do know it, Gaby.

549
00:24:06,596 --> 00:24:10,692
I'd like to meet my new friend,
Mr. Waldo.

550
00:24:10,724 --> 00:24:13,988
He looks scary. Like a lion.

551
00:24:14,020 --> 00:24:15,748
Yeah, but he's a friendly lion.

552
00:24:15,780 --> 00:24:18,884
Gaby and I are going to spend
some daddy time before bed,

553
00:24:18,916 --> 00:24:20,804
- you snuggly baby.
- GABY: [ Laughing ]

554
00:24:20,836 --> 00:24:25,732
Oh, you haven't decided
to take the case yet, have you?

555
00:24:25,764 --> 00:24:27,428
What say you, Detective?

556
00:24:27,460 --> 00:24:30,756
Will you return to your mountain
and leave me to the fates?

557
00:24:30,788 --> 00:24:33,028
Or will you stick around
the shitty of the angels

558
00:24:33,060 --> 00:24:36,612
long enough to see the police
maybe get it right this time?

559
00:24:36,644 --> 00:24:38,403
Whatever right may look like.

560
00:24:38,436 --> 00:24:41,796
GABY: Daddy, can Mr. Lion drive
to school with us tomorrow?

561
00:24:41,828 --> 00:24:43,748
Can he please?

562
00:24:43,780 --> 00:24:45,796
Please?

563
00:24:45,827 --> 00:24:47,716
♪♪

564
00:24:47,747 --> 00:24:49,604
Yay!

565
00:24:49,636 --> 00:24:55,748
♪♪

566
00:24:55,779 --> 00:24:57,476
ROSARIO:
Will this be all right?

567
00:24:57,508 --> 00:24:59,652
♪♪

568
00:24:59,684 --> 00:25:01,091
It's perfect.

569
00:25:01,124 --> 00:25:07,907
♪♪

570
00:25:07,940 --> 00:25:09,604
Fucking Lorena.

571
00:25:09,636 --> 00:25:16,324
♪♪

572
00:25:16,356 --> 00:25:23,011
♪♪

573
00:25:23,044 --> 00:25:25,956
[ <i>Dramatic music playing</i>
<i>on television</i> ]

574
00:25:32,292 --> 00:25:35,812
<i>Guilty.</i>

575
00:25:35,844 --> 00:25:37,348
<i>...and turn down the volume
on the media circus.</i>

576
00:25:37,380 --> 00:25:38,627
WOMAN:
<i>Oh, come on, Fontella.</i>

577
00:25:38,660 --> 00:25:40,388
<i>You live for the media circus.</i>

578
00:25:40,420 --> 00:25:41,732
<i>Now I'm hearing there could be
an indictment</i>

579
00:25:41,763 --> 00:25:43,140
<i>as early as tomorrow.</i>

580
00:25:43,171 --> 00:25:44,612
FONTELLA:
<i>We've not been told that.</i>

581
00:25:44,643 --> 00:25:46,020
WOMAN: <i>And now the</i> L.A. Times
<i>is reporting</i>

582
00:25:46,051 --> 00:25:47,396
<i>that sources on the LAPD say</i>

583
00:25:47,427 --> 00:25:49,252
<i>there are no
unidentified fingerprints</i>

584
00:25:49,284 --> 00:25:50,372
<i>anywhere in that room.</i>

585
00:25:50,403 --> 00:25:51,940
<i>What does that suggest to you?</i>

586
00:25:51,971 --> 00:25:53,252
FONTELLA: <i>It suggests that
the real killer</i>

587
00:25:53,283 --> 00:25:54,788
<i>knew what he was doing.</i>

588
00:25:54,820 --> 00:25:55,811
WOMAN: <i>You promised us
Charlie Waldo</i>

589
00:25:55,844 --> 00:25:57,219
<i>from the Lydell Lipps case.</i>

590
00:25:57,252 --> 00:25:58,947
<i>What does it say
that he's not here with you?</i>

591
00:25:58,980 --> 00:26:00,804
FONTELLA: <i>Charlie Waldo
is busy uncovering...</i>

592
00:26:00,836 --> 00:26:02,019
[ Television shuts off ]

593
00:26:04,580 --> 00:26:09,251
♪♪

594
00:26:09,284 --> 00:26:12,900
Welcome to kindergartens
of the rich and famous.

595
00:26:12,931 --> 00:26:15,107
Gaby, Mr. Lion needs to
talk to your teacher.

596
00:26:15,140 --> 00:26:17,700
But first, he's going to
park this beast.

597
00:26:17,731 --> 00:26:19,940
Now get out, little blighter.

598
00:26:19,972 --> 00:26:21,540
[ Laughs ]

599
00:26:22,820 --> 00:26:24,068
Baby back ribs in there.

600
00:26:24,099 --> 00:26:27,364
GABY: [ Giggles ]

601
00:26:27,395 --> 00:26:29,540
ALASTAIR:
Alas, poor Yorick!

602
00:26:29,572 --> 00:26:31,524
I knew him, my sweet Gaby,

603
00:26:31,556 --> 00:26:35,171
a fellow of infinite jest,
of most excellent fancy.

604
00:26:35,204 --> 00:26:37,795
He hath borne me on his back
a thousand times,

605
00:26:37,828 --> 00:26:40,132
and now, how abhorred
in my imagination it is!

606
00:26:40,164 --> 00:26:41,891
My gorge rises at it.

607
00:26:41,924 --> 00:26:44,740
Yes, you're a shadow
of your former self.

608
00:26:44,771 --> 00:26:46,212
[ High-pitched voice ]
It's that keto diet I'm on.

609
00:26:46,244 --> 00:26:48,996
I'm starving. I think I may have
taken it a bit too far.

610
00:26:49,028 --> 00:26:50,340
You got anything in your lunch?

611
00:26:50,371 --> 00:26:52,547
Like a pork chop?
Ham sandwich? No?

612
00:26:52,580 --> 00:26:53,700
[ Normal voice ] I'm afraid it
wouldn't do you any good,

613
00:26:53,732 --> 00:26:55,524
dear boy.
I think you're dead.

614
00:26:55,556 --> 00:26:57,251
[ High-pitched voice ]
Dead? That's tragic.

615
00:26:57,284 --> 00:27:00,387
[ Normal voice ]
Yes, indeed, it's tragic.

616
00:27:00,420 --> 00:27:02,211
Where be your gibes now?

617
00:27:02,244 --> 00:27:04,771
Your gambols? Your songs?

618
00:27:04,804 --> 00:27:06,084
Your flashes of merriment

619
00:27:06,116 --> 00:27:09,092
that were wont to set the table
on a roar?

620
00:27:09,123 --> 00:27:10,787
GABY: [ Giggles ]

621
00:27:10,820 --> 00:27:12,484
ALASTAIR: I think
I've soiled my britches.

622
00:27:12,515 --> 00:27:15,395
Should I change my nappy?
Oh, it's all squishy.

623
00:27:15,428 --> 00:27:17,315
- GABY: Bravo!
- [ Applause ]

624
00:27:17,348 --> 00:27:18,627
Oh, yes, thank you, thank you.

625
00:27:18,660 --> 00:27:20,291
GABY: That was funny, Daddy.

626
00:27:20,324 --> 00:27:23,460
Yes. That speech
always slays them.

627
00:27:23,492 --> 00:27:25,539
Come. Let's play on the swings.

628
00:27:25,573 --> 00:27:27,971
I believe Mr. Lion
wants to ask Miss White

629
00:27:28,004 --> 00:27:30,212
whether Daddy plays nicely with
the other children.

630
00:27:30,243 --> 00:27:31,907
Off we go.
Let's get to the swings.

631
00:27:31,940 --> 00:27:34,820
- It'll be a swinging time.
- GABY: Swing, swing, swing!

632
00:27:34,851 --> 00:27:37,348
WALDO:
My name's Waldo.

633
00:27:37,379 --> 00:27:39,331
I'm a detective
working for Alastair.

634
00:27:39,364 --> 00:27:42,436
JAYNE: Jayne.
My heart breaks for Gaby.

635
00:27:42,467 --> 00:27:46,244
Mr. Pinch is doing a lot
to keep her spirits up.

636
00:27:46,276 --> 00:27:49,251
And Mrs. Pinch...
What was she like as a parent?

637
00:27:51,811 --> 00:27:54,243
Mrs. Pinch?

638
00:27:54,276 --> 00:27:56,708
[ Sighs ]

639
00:27:56,740 --> 00:27:59,108
We have the children memorize
these poems.

640
00:27:59,140 --> 00:28:03,299
I like to ask the kids whose mom
and dad can recite them too.

641
00:28:03,331 --> 00:28:04,707
Half the time
these parents can't,

642
00:28:04,740 --> 00:28:08,612
but the nanny can
in two languages.

643
00:28:08,643 --> 00:28:10,660
What about the Pinches?

644
00:28:10,693 --> 00:28:12,291
Mrs. Pinch never knew them.

645
00:28:12,324 --> 00:28:15,971
Mr. Pinch, always.

646
00:28:16,004 --> 00:28:18,659
That's unusual.

647
00:28:18,691 --> 00:28:20,931
The death must have shocked
the hell out of this place, huh?

648
00:28:20,964 --> 00:28:22,691
[ Bell rings ]

649
00:28:22,724 --> 00:28:24,419
Not me.

650
00:28:25,860 --> 00:28:27,395
[ Children shouting ]

651
00:28:27,428 --> 00:28:28,707
Good morning, kids.

652
00:28:28,740 --> 00:28:31,204
Okay, everyone find their place.
Get your bunnies.

653
00:28:31,235 --> 00:28:32,995
We're gonna start by writing
your names on the back of them,

654
00:28:33,028 --> 00:28:35,011
so have a marker.

655
00:28:35,044 --> 00:28:38,403
Miss White, I'm gonna need
to talk to you again.

656
00:28:38,437 --> 00:28:39,875
Sure.

657
00:28:42,180 --> 00:28:44,708
Does everyone have their bunny
from yesterday?

658
00:28:48,164 --> 00:28:50,852
Come meet me tonight.
We can talk then.

659
00:28:52,868 --> 00:28:55,204
All right.
Have you got names set?

660
00:28:55,235 --> 00:28:56,740
CHILDREN:
Yes, Miss White.

661
00:28:56,773 --> 00:29:03,779
♪♪

662
00:29:03,811 --> 00:29:10,628
♪♪

663
00:29:10,660 --> 00:29:17,475
♪♪

664
00:29:17,507 --> 00:29:18,596
[ Sniffs ]

665
00:29:18,627 --> 00:29:20,740
♪♪

666
00:29:20,773 --> 00:29:23,620
[ Lighter clicking ]

667
00:29:23,653 --> 00:29:31,780
♪♪

668
00:29:31,811 --> 00:29:39,716
♪♪

669
00:29:39,747 --> 00:29:47,939
♪♪

670
00:29:53,124 --> 00:29:56,067
Do you put your boots
on your chairs at home?

671
00:29:56,100 --> 00:29:58,403
I live in a trailer
with a chicken.

672
00:29:59,811 --> 00:30:02,724
What happened to this "vayse"?

673
00:30:02,756 --> 00:30:05,540
"Vahse."

674
00:30:05,571 --> 00:30:09,124
Ah, yes. Well...

675
00:30:09,155 --> 00:30:11,331
That's the one
she was killed with.

676
00:30:13,284 --> 00:30:14,819
What was that, ceramic?

677
00:30:14,851 --> 00:30:17,124
Earthenware.
Nice vase. I rather miss it.

678
00:30:17,156 --> 00:30:18,915
What about that table?

679
00:30:20,675 --> 00:30:21,956
It's different.

680
00:30:21,987 --> 00:30:23,907
[ Sighs ] Monica was a tinkerer.

681
00:30:23,941 --> 00:30:27,620
No room was ever finished
to her satisfaction.

682
00:30:27,651 --> 00:30:31,491
Mm. And that sculpture.

683
00:30:31,524 --> 00:30:33,059
The Bard?

684
00:30:33,091 --> 00:30:34,693
The sculpture.

685
00:30:34,724 --> 00:30:36,517
This.

686
00:30:38,084 --> 00:30:39,971
Ah, dear boy.

687
00:30:40,004 --> 00:30:44,101
That's a Regis Award
for my Richard III.

688
00:30:44,132 --> 00:30:45,604
Did you move it?

689
00:30:45,635 --> 00:30:48,836
I've never been much
for acting trophies.

690
00:30:48,868 --> 00:30:51,748
Monica had that one on display
for sentimental reasons.

691
00:30:51,781 --> 00:30:53,475
That was the production
on which we met.

692
00:30:53,507 --> 00:30:55,075
Really?

693
00:30:55,108 --> 00:30:57,955
Perhaps it's wherever Monica
put my other Regises

694
00:30:57,988 --> 00:31:02,276
or my... People's Choice Award.

695
00:31:02,308 --> 00:31:03,779
[ Belches ]

696
00:31:03,811 --> 00:31:05,635
Good night, sweet prince.

697
00:31:05,668 --> 00:31:08,132
Flights of angels
sing thee to thy rest.

698
00:31:08,164 --> 00:31:11,012
[ Choir singing indistinctly ]

699
00:31:11,044 --> 00:31:17,315
♪♪

700
00:31:17,348 --> 00:31:21,059
CHOIR:
♪ In the old rugged cross ♪

701
00:31:21,091 --> 00:31:24,613
♪ Stained with blood so divine ♪

702
00:31:24,644 --> 00:31:30,980
♪ A wondrous beauty I see ♪

703
00:31:31,011 --> 00:31:35,588
♪ For 'twas on that old cross ♪

704
00:31:35,619 --> 00:31:39,428
♪ Jesus suffered and died ♪

705
00:31:39,459 --> 00:31:42,467
♪ To pardon and sanctify me ♪

706
00:31:42,500 --> 00:31:46,051
There goes the good girl
kindergarten teacher.

707
00:31:46,083 --> 00:31:50,115
Just wait till I have
a few Maker's in me.

708
00:31:50,147 --> 00:31:53,156
So why weren't you shocked
that Monica Pinch was killed?

709
00:31:53,188 --> 00:31:59,845
♪♪

710
00:31:59,876 --> 00:32:04,228
Okay, Mr. Waldo.

711
00:32:04,259 --> 00:32:06,275
I have a confession.

712
00:32:06,308 --> 00:32:09,219
Okay.

713
00:32:09,251 --> 00:32:11,108
I've been watching
all this TV coverage

714
00:32:11,139 --> 00:32:12,356
since the murder.

715
00:32:15,492 --> 00:32:16,995
I knew exactly who you were

716
00:32:17,027 --> 00:32:19,011
the minute you walked into
my classroom.

717
00:32:19,045 --> 00:32:21,443
That figures.

718
00:32:26,371 --> 00:32:28,291
Who was Lydell Lipps?

719
00:32:28,323 --> 00:32:31,652
Everyone keeps talking
about Lydell Lipps.

720
00:32:31,684 --> 00:32:38,180
♪♪

721
00:32:38,212 --> 00:32:40,357
I can usually tell when
someone's messing with me.

722
00:32:40,388 --> 00:32:43,045
You're jamming up my radar.

723
00:32:43,076 --> 00:32:45,603
Maybe your radar's just rusty.

724
00:32:48,068 --> 00:32:49,765
Yeah, maybe.

725
00:32:50,084 --> 00:32:52,228
Here you go.

726
00:32:52,259 --> 00:32:53,892
JAYNE:
Thanks.

727
00:32:53,924 --> 00:32:58,597
♪♪

728
00:32:58,628 --> 00:33:00,260
To whiskey and good hair.

729
00:33:00,292 --> 00:33:06,723
♪♪

730
00:33:06,755 --> 00:33:12,996
♪♪

731
00:33:13,028 --> 00:33:14,660
It's been a while.

732
00:33:14,692 --> 00:33:24,195
♪♪

733
00:33:24,227 --> 00:33:26,147
Okay. If you want to know,
I'll tell you.

734
00:33:26,180 --> 00:33:32,164
♪♪

735
00:33:32,196 --> 00:33:36,483
11 years ago,
there was a robbery at 7-11.

736
00:33:36,515 --> 00:33:39,908
The girl behind the counter
and two customers

737
00:33:39,940 --> 00:33:41,251
got shot dead.

738
00:33:41,283 --> 00:33:45,059
I turned up a kid
named Donny Lipps.

739
00:33:45,091 --> 00:33:46,372
Leaned on him pretty hard.

740
00:33:46,405 --> 00:33:47,875
It paid off.

741
00:33:47,907 --> 00:33:50,115
He said he was waiting
in the car outside.

742
00:33:50,148 --> 00:33:52,068
And in return for a deal,

743
00:33:52,100 --> 00:33:54,372
he would give me the shooter.

744
00:33:54,404 --> 00:33:57,988
Turns out that was Lydell,
his brother.

745
00:33:58,021 --> 00:34:00,805
Signed, sealed.

746
00:34:00,836 --> 00:34:02,499
My career's off to the races,
right,

747
00:34:02,531 --> 00:34:05,315
and I am on fire with ambition.

748
00:34:05,348 --> 00:34:07,492
Everything's going great.

749
00:34:07,525 --> 00:34:09,732
Cut to years later.

750
00:34:09,764 --> 00:34:11,556
Lydell comes up for parole,

751
00:34:11,588 --> 00:34:14,468
and the prosecutors ask me to
help them prep for the hearing.

752
00:34:14,500 --> 00:34:16,165
So I go see the brother again,

753
00:34:16,196 --> 00:34:17,859
who's in prison himself
at this point.

754
00:34:17,891 --> 00:34:19,748
Three strikes, unrelated.

755
00:34:21,635 --> 00:34:27,556
Only now he tells me that
the original story was bullshit.

756
00:34:27,588 --> 00:34:31,299
He made it up
to get me off his back.

757
00:34:35,204 --> 00:34:36,612
So at that point,

758
00:34:36,644 --> 00:34:38,341
Lydell had been in jail for...

759
00:34:38,372 --> 00:34:42,020
7 years, 3 months, and 16 days.

760
00:34:44,260 --> 00:34:46,595
Well, next thing I learn,

761
00:34:46,628 --> 00:34:49,892
it is a lot harder to get
an innocent man out of jail

762
00:34:49,924 --> 00:34:52,451
than to put a guilty man in.

763
00:34:52,484 --> 00:34:54,852
System isn't designed
to deal with mistakes.

764
00:34:54,884 --> 00:34:58,019
And some individuals aren't,
either.

